Date: Wed, 26 Jul 2000 05:48:50 -0400
From: Eleanor Kellon <kell@epix.net>

Progress of the West Nile virus outbreak
----------------------------------------
I was disappointed with both the attitude and the content in the last West
Nile posting. The number of positive dead birds has doubled in the last
week or two. Mosquito pool positives occurred for the first time in the
last week or two. Positives are rising rapidly despite what would be
considered aggressive larvicidal measures, necessitating the ground
sprayings. Sentinel chickens appear to either be worthless or not
positioned properly. Reported sightings of dead birds have numbered in the
thousands in those areas effected last year, much less (often under 100) in
uninvolved counties in New York state. These numbers, which are most
definitely not small, may be the most significant of all. All states and
counties that had positives last year have now had positives (bird or
mosquito) this year, which was not the case two weeks ago. The situation is
building rapidly, not slowly. Perhaps of even more concern is that endemic
viruses (EEE, SLE) being tested for concurrently are not showing this early
(for mosquito-borne diseases) activity, suggesting it is not related solely
to mosquito numbers.
I agree the posts could get tiresome, particularly if they continue to
quote joggers from Central Park or physicians who "fear" the most
over-diagnosed disease in the Western hemisphere more than an encephalitis
virus introduced into virgin territory. [Indeed, I have been informed by a
ProMED-mail colleague that both deer and Lyme disease-infected ticks have
been found in both Central Park NYC and Hyde Park, London. - Mod.CP. Such
material should be left on the pages of the New York Times.
--
Eleanor Kellon, VMD
Technical Editor
Horse Journal
<kell@epix.net>
