Date: Sun, 16 Jul 2000 21:33:58 -0700
From: Rick Lehtinen <lehtinenfamily@home.com>

Sentinel ducks
--------------
I understand the need to limit West Nile Virus coverage until there is
something new to cover, but one area I'd like to keep open for discussion
is the possibility of using sentinel ducks instead of chickens. As was
reported from the Bronx Zoo(?), ducks seroconvert more readily and can hold
more of the virus without dying, hence these birds are seemingly better
suited to this function. In addition, ducks habitats include the kinds of
ponds in which mosquitoes breed. Ducks are more sedentary, and hence
would be easier targets for mosquitoes. Ducks can be easily captured for
examination with a handful of grain and a simple shepherd's crook, and
ducks do not require confinement. They will pretty much hang out where you
put them if there is water and the occasional handful of mash. It may even
be possible to band and monitor ducks that already reside in the suspected
areas.
--
Rick Lehtinen
<lehtinenfamily@home.com>
