Date: Tue, 25 Jul 2000 09:09:51 -0400
From: Turell, Michael J Dr USAMRIID <Michael.Turell@DET.AMEDD.ARMY.MIL>

Potential of _Culex restuans_ for transmission of West Nile virus
---------------------------------------------------------------
The detection of West Nile (WN) virus activity in crows earlier this
summer, before _Culex pipiens_ should have been active in large numbers,
raised the question of the potential for _Culex restuans_ to transmit WN
virus by bite. The recent detection of WN virus in _Cx. restuans_
mosquitoes from Connecticut by Dr. Anderson further raises this question.
As part of our evaluation of potential vectors of WN virus we tested both
_Cx. restuans_ and _Cx. pipiens_. Although our data for _Cx. restuans_ is
preliminary, in the laboratory it appears very similar to _Cx. pipiens_ in
its ability to transmit WN virus (i.e., it is a moderately efficient
vector). HOWEVER, the ability to transmit a virus in the laboratory is just
one factor in determining its vectorial capacity. Of greater importance are
host-feeding preference, population density, and survival relative to the
extrinsic incubation period.
I read with interest a ProMED-mail report yesterday that stated that "The
bird virus [West Nile virus that killed seven New Yorkers last year has
now spread all over the Americas..." To the best of my knowledge, there has
not been any indication that this virus has spread this year beyond the New
York, New Jersey, Connecticut area. Similarly, there is no evidence that
the virus came into the US in a bird from Israel. Likewise, there is
considerable evidence that the virus responsible for the current outbreak
is distinct from the one used in the 1950's studies at the Sloan-Kettering
Institute in New York.
--
Michael J. Turell
Virology Division, USAMRIID
Fort Detrick, MD 21702
<Michael.Turell@DET.AMEDD.ARMY.MIL>
